eu.trentorise.opendata.traceprov.dcat

Class AbstractDcatCatalog

  • java.lang.Object
    • eu.trentorise.opendata.traceprov.dcat.AbstractDcatCatalog

  • @Value.Immutable
public abstract class AbstractDcatCatalog
extends Object
    A data catalog is a curated collection of metadata about datasets, as specified by dcat:catalog Typically, a web-based data catalog is represented as a single instance of this class. Following properties were not included:
    List datasets and List records
    Author:
    David Leoni

      • getHomepage

        @Value.Default
public String getHomepage()
        The homepage of the catalog. It should be unique and precisely identify the catalog. This allows smushing various descriptions of the catalog when different URIs are used. Specified by foaf:homepage

      • getIssued

        public abstract com.google.common.base.Optional<org.joda.time.DateTime> getIssued()
        Date of formal issuance (e.g., publication) of the catalog, as specified by dct:issued Note DCAT standard requires dates in string format to be ISO 8601 Date and Time compliant string format i.e. "2011-12-11".
        See Also:
        AbstractDcatDataset.getIssued(), AbstractDcatDistribution.getIssued(), AbstractDcatCatalogRecord.getIssued()

      • getLanguages

        public abstract List<Locale> getLanguages()
        The languages of the catalog. This refers to the language used in the textual metadata describing titles, descriptions, etc. of the datasets in the catalog. The publisher might also choose to describe the language on the dataset level. Java Locale should be created out of language codes defined by the Library of Congress (ISO 639-1, ISO 639-2). If a ISO 639-1 (two-letter) code is defined for language, then its corresponding IRI should be used; if no ISO 639-1 code is defined, then IRI corresponding to the ISO 639-2 (three-letter) code should be used.
        See Also:
        AbstractDcatDataset.getLanguages()

      • getLicense

        @Value.Default
public String getLicense()
        This links to the license document under which the catalog is made available and not the datasets. Even if the license of the catalog applies to all of its datasets and distributions, it should be replicated on each distribution. Specified by dct:license

      • getModified

        public abstract com.google.common.base.Optional<org.joda.time.DateTime> getModified()
        Most recent date on which the catalog was changed, updated or modified. Must be in a ISO 8601 Date and Time compliant string format i.e. "2011-12-11" . Specified by dct:modified

      • getPublisher

      • getRights

        @Value.Default
public String getRights()
        This describes the rights under which the catalog can be used/reused and not the datasets . Even if these rights apply to all the catalog datasets and distributions, it should be replicated on each distribution. Specified by dct:rights.
        See Also:
        getLicense(), AbstractDcatDistribution.getRights()

      • getSpatial

      • getCategories

        @Value.Default
public AbstractSkosConceptScheme getCategories()
        The taxonomy of categories used to classify catalog's datasets, as specified by dcat:themeTaxonomy . Note the property name in the specs is 'themes' but 'categories' is also used as synonim in other places of the specs and seems more natural. When field is not available SkosConceptScheme.of() is returned.
        See Also:
        AbstractDcatDataset.getCategories()

      • getTitle

        @Value.Default
public Dict getTitle()
        A name given to the catalog, as specified by dct:title

      • getUri

        @Value.Default
public String getUri()
        Property not in DCAT spec. This should uniquely identify the catalog, giving the same result as getHomepage()
